Preheat your oven to 180°C. Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and chopped). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Pop the @tenderstem broccoli{150g} on a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @olive oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Set aside.

Halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125%g}. Pop the @cider vinegar{15%ml}, @honey{15%ml} and @olive oil{1%tbsp} into a #medium sized bowl{}. Season with @salt and @pepper and mix together. Add the tomatoes, mix and set aside. Crumble the @feta cheese{100%g} into small pieces.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #saucepan{} on medium-high heat. Add the onion and cook, stirring frequently until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}, then add the garlic and @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g}. Stir continuously and cook for ~{1%minute}. Stir the orzo and @vegetable stock powder{1} into the pan followed by the @water{450%ml}.

Bring to a simmer, stirring to combine, then reduce the heat to medium-low and simmer until the orzo is cooked and the liquid absorbed, ~{10-12%minutes}. Stir every couple of minutes to ensure the orzo is not sticking to the bottom of the pan. If the mixture is looking a bit dry and the orzo is not quite cooked, just add a splash of water and keep cooking.

Meanwhile, roast the broccoli on the top shelf of your oven until tender, ~{10-12%minutes}. Once the orzo is cooked, remove from the heat. Stir in the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} until melted. Taste and add @salt{} and @pepper{} if you feel it needs it.

Serve the orzo in #bowls{} with the roasted broccoli on one side and the tomato salsa on the other side, sprinkle with the crumbled feta. Enjoy!